</span></h1><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Role_of_L_D_professionals_in_changing_learning_cultures_in_organisations_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102276" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Role_of_L_D_professionals_in_changing_learning_cultures_in_organisations_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102276 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Role_of_L_D_professionals_in_changing_learning_cultures_in_organisations_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_1000x.jpg?v=1694102276 768w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Role_of_L_D_professionals_in_changing_learning_cultures_in_organisations_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1694102276 320w" width="2080" height="1387" alt="The role of learning and development professionals in transforming learning cultures in organisations - Dr Richard Dune -" title="The role of learning and development professionals in transforming learning cultures in organisations - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-14_"/></div></div></div></div></div><div data-section-id="pf-c064" data-category="Generic Content" data-name="Matcha" data-pf-type="Section" class="sc-hAcGzb jHOovW pf-15_"><div style="--cw:1170px" class="sc-eGPXGI cIlovf"><div class="sc-iCfMLu eehqFj pf-16_ pf-r pf-r-eh" style="--s-xs:0px;--s-sm:15px" data-pf-type="Row"><div class="pf-c" style="--c-xs:12;--c-md:12;--c-lg:12"><div data-pf-type="Column" class="sc-XxNYO eWQzGj pf-17_"><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-18_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-20_">In today's rapidly evolving business landscape, organisations need constant learning and development to stay ahead of the competition. This has led to a significant transformation of learning cultures, focusing on equipping employees with the necessary skills to adapt to change and achieve business objectives.<br>
<br>In this article, <a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/dr-richard-dune-blog" target="_blank"><i><span style="color: rgb(0, 102, 204);">Dr Richard Dune</span></i></a> will discuss the important role of learning and development (L&amp;D) professionals in transforming learning cultures within organisations.<br>
</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-21_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-23_">How L&amp;D professionals can transform learning cultures
</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/How_L_D_professionals_can_transform_learning_cultures_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102428" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/How_L_D_professionals_can_transform_learning_cultures_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102428 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/How_L_D_professionals_can_transform_learning_cultures_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1694102428 320w" width="2000" height="1500" alt="How organisational learning can help businesses adapt and achieve objectives - Dr Richard Dune -" title="How organisational learning can help businesses adapt and achieve objectives - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-24_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-25_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-27_"><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/leadership-mastery" target="_blank"><i><span style="color: rgb(0, 71, 178);"></span></i></a>Learning and development professionals must collaborate with others to change the learning culture in organisations. They should focus on the following factors:
<br>
</span></p><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-jHkVzv gbyaRg pf-28_"><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-29_">Questioning and influencing for improvement</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-31_">Attending staff and management meetings</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-33_">Engaging with key influencers</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-35_">Using key questions to facilitate action and change in culture.</li></ul><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-37_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-39_"><a href="https://www.mandatorytraining.co.uk/pages/leadership-mastery" target="_blank"><i><span style="color: rgb(0, 71, 178);"></span></i></a>By working on these factors, L&amp;D professionals can drive a shift towards a more positive and inclusive learning culture.
<br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-40_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-42_">Questioning and influencing for improvement
</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Questioning_and_influencing_for_improvement_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102519" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Questioning_and_influencing_for_improvement_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102519 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Questioning_and_influencing_for_improvement_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1694102519 320w" width="2430" height="1668" alt="Mandatory training programs: Enhancing skills for a positive learning culture - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Mandatory training programs: Enhancing skills for a positive learning culture - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-43_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-44_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-46_">L&amp;D professionals can use their skills in questioning and influencing to collaborate with their employer and deliver a high-quality mandatory training program that fosters a positive culture and engages staff. This involves analysing information to identify workplace issues and intervening proactively, picking up on issues before they become significant problems.<br>
<br>L&amp;D professionals can work with other trade union colleagues and employers to address issues promptly and positively. They can also identify areas of excellence and share them widely across the organisation.<br>
</span></p><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-47_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-49_">Staff and management meetings
</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Staff_and_management_meetings_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102640" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Staff_and_management_meetings_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102640 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Staff_and_management_meetings_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1694102640 320w" width="2645" height="1764" alt="Collaborating for change: Improving learning cultures in the workplace - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Collaborating for change: Improving learning cultures in the workplace - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-50_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-51_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-53_">L&amp;D professionals can work with their employers to create a committee or forum where staff can discuss decisions that affect them and their services. These committees can effectively address concerns, share good practices and gain support for ideas for improvement. Union representatives are typically part of these committees, with the chair and secretary roles often taken on by union representatives.<br>
<br>Health and safety committees are beneficial in addressing safety concerns related to mandatory training. L&amp;D professionals can also suggest a partnership approach to improving mandatory training if their organisation doesn't have a formal committee or forum.<br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-54_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-56_">Engaging with key influencers
</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Engaging_with_key_influencers_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102791" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Engaging_with_key_influencers_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102791 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Engaging_with_key_influencers_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1694102791 320w" width="2000" height="1333" alt="Addressing workplace issues through effective learning and development strategies - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Addressing workplace issues through effective learning and development strategies - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-57_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-58_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-60_">Before improving mandatory training, checking if the organisation has a partnership forum or committee is necessary. Identifying the committee chair and secretary and who represents the organisation is essential.<br>
<br>It is also important to know the process for raising an agenda item. Without a committee or forum, L&amp;D professionals should identify the key influencers and enablers of training and health and safety and arrange a meeting to discuss the possibility of working together.<br>
</span></p><h3 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-61_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-63_">Key questions to facilitate action and a change of culture</span></h3><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Key_questions_to_facilitate_action_and_a_change_of_culture_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102881" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Key_questions_to_facilitate_action_and_a_change_of_culture_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102881 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Key_questions_to_facilitate_action_and_a_change_of_culture_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1694102881 320w" width="2482" height="1655" alt="Key questions to facilitate action and a change of culture - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Key questions to facilitate action and a change of culture - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-64_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-65_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-67_">These questions are designed to gather information on current provisions, compliance, and culture surrounding mandatory training in an organisation. They can be used to develop an action plan for change:

<br>
</span></p><ul style="--text-indent:0;--line-spacing:10px" data-pf-type="List2" class="sc-jHkVzv gbyaRg pf-68_"><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-69_"><b>Time and cost</b> - How is mandatory training delivered, and at what cost? Are staff released from work to complete the training?</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-71_"><b>Quality and relevance</b> - Does the training program reflect the experience and role of individual staff? Are refresher courses offered? Is mandatory training evaluated regularly?</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-73_"><b>Access and inclusion</b> - Can part-time and night workers access training during their working hours? Do all staff have access to IT equipment to complete online training?</li><li tabindex="0" spellcheck="false" data-pf-type="List2.Item2" class="sc-bQtKYq wvgEH pf-75_"><b>Culture</b> - What are the attitudes and perceptions around mandatory training? What is the current compliance rate, and why are some workers non-compliant? Are workers from agencies given adequate training to reflect the organisation's culture? These questions can form the basis of an action plan for improving mandatory training.</li></ul><h2 data-pf-type="Heading" class="sc-hOGkXu NrNIR pf-77_ _Y6RW61"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-79_">Conclusion
</span></h2><img src="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Role_of_L_D_professionals_in_changing_the_learning_culture_-_Conclusion_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102970" srcSet="https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Role_of_L_D_professionals_in_changing_the_learning_culture_-_Conclusion_-_Dr_Richard_Dune.jpg?v=1694102970 1536w, https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0937/2788/files/Role_of_L_D_professionals_in_changing_the_learning_culture_-_Conclusion_-_Dr_Richard_Dune_500x.jpg?v=1694102970 320w" width="2000" height="1333" alt="Role of L&D professionals in changing the learning culture - Conclusion - Dr Richard Dune -" title="Role of L&D professionals in changing the learning culture - Conclusion - Dr Richard Dune -" data-pf-type="Image3" class="sc-bXTejn eKvewz pf-80_"/><p class="sc-FNXRL jGHEAN pf-81_" data-pf-type="Paragraph"><span data-pf-type="Text" class="sc-gyElHZ fxaypC pf-83_">Learning and development (L&amp;D) professionals are crucial in transforming organisational learning cultures. They can drive a shift towards a more positive and inclusive learning culture.<br>
